<font face="Serif" size="18">we were so blessed
to have in our congregation</font>

356
00:20:11,426 --> 00:20:16,398
<font face="Serif" size="18">a graduate of the 7th class of Gilead,
Brother Fred Wiens.</font>

357
00:20:16,398 --> 00:20:20,202
<font face="Serif" size="18">Brother Wiens was an anointed brother
who was baptized</font>

358
00:20:20,202 --> 00:20:22,571
<font face="Serif" size="18">in 1928.</font>

359
00:20:22,571 --> 00:20:25,007
<font face="Serif" size="18">Now, I’ll be honest with you;</font>

360
00:20:25,007 --> 00:20:29,811
<font face="Serif" size="18">I don’t remember even one talk
that Fred Wiens gave.</font>

361
00:20:29,811 --> 00:20:33,982
<font face="Serif" size="18">But his warmth, his sense of humor,</font>

362
00:20:33,982 --> 00:20:37,819
<font face="Serif" size="18">his zeal for the ministry,
and his love for people</font>

363
00:20:37,819 --> 00:20:40,489
<font face="Serif" size="18">—the example that he set—</font>

364
00:20:40,489 --> 00:20:43,325
<font face="Serif" size="18">is truly unforgettable.</font>

365
00:20:43,325 --> 00:20:45,294
<font face="Serif" size="18">Fred talked to everyone</font>

366
00:20:45,294 --> 00:20:48,397
<font face="Serif" size="18">—and I mean everyone—
in the ministry.</font>

367
00:20:48,397 --> 00:20:52,901
<font face="Serif" size="18">One time we were out in service;
we pulled into the gas station.</font>

368
00:20:52,901 --> 00:20:55,737
<font face="Serif" size="18">As soon as we stopped the car,
Fred jumped out.</font>

369
00:20:55,737 --> 00:20:57,873
<font face="Serif" size="18">And when we were ready to leave,</font>

370
00:20:57,873 --> 00:21:00,475
<font face="Serif" size="18">we looked around to try to find Fred.</font>

371
00:21:00,475 --> 00:21:03,478
<font face="Serif" size="18">He wasn’t in the store;
he wasn’t in the bathroom.</font>

372
00:21:03,478 --> 00:21:05,380
<font face="Serif" size="18">He was nowhere to be seen.</font>

373
00:21:05,380 --> 00:21:08,417
<font face="Serif" size="18">Finally, we thought
we’d check the other cars.</font>

374
00:21:08,417 --> 00:21:11,153
<font face="Serif" size="18">Well, that’s exactly where Fred was.</font>

375
00:21:11,153 --> 00:21:14,389
<font face="Serif" size="18">Fred had knocked on the window
and gotten in a car</font>

376
00:21:14,389 --> 00:21:19,027
<font face="Serif" size="18">and started to preach
to all the people in that car.</font>

377
00:21:19,027 --> 00:21:22,731
<font face="Serif" size="18">Fred has now gone on to his reward.</font>

378
00:21:22,731 --> 00:21:26,501
<font face="Serif" size="18">But his example of warmth, kindness,</font>

379
00:21:26,501 --> 00:21:31,106
<font face="Serif" size="18">zeal, and love for people
continue to teach me</font>

380
00:21:31,106 --> 00:21:35,677
<font face="Serif" size="18">—and many others who knew him well—
right down to this day.</font>

381
00:21:35,677 --> 00:21:40,349
<font face="Serif" size="18">So here is the question
that rests before you:</font>

382
00:21:40,349 --> 00:21:45,187
<font face="Serif" size="18">What will you teach others by your example?</font>

383
00:21:45,187 --> 00:21:47,222
<font face="Serif" size="18">Be like Paul.</font>

384
00:21:47,222 --> 00:21:51,126
<font face="Serif" size="18">Love your brothers and sisters
right from your heart.</font>

385
00:21:51,126 --> 00:21:53,228
<font face="Serif" size="18">Through your example,</font>

386
00:21:53,228 --> 00:21:57,265
<font face="Serif" size="18">create an atmosphere of warmth and love</font>

387
00:21:57,265 --> 00:22:00,702
<font face="Serif" size="18">like a greenhouse
where young plants</font>

388
00:22:00,702 --> 00:22:03,405
<font face="Serif" size="18">can blossom and grow.</font>

389
00:22:03,405 --> 00:22:07,743
<font face="Serif" size="18">Your fine example
can warm up a congregation,</font>

390
00:22:07,743 --> 00:22:12,748
<font face="Serif" size="18">a circuit, a Bethel department,
perhaps even a branch office.</font>

391
00:22:12,748 --> 00:22:15,784
<font face="Serif" size="18">Never allow yourself</font>

392
00:22:15,784 --> 00:22:19,287
<font face="Serif" size="18">to be a cold executive</font>

393
00:22:19,287 --> 00:22:24,192
<font face="Serif" size="18">who creates an atmosphere like a freezer,</font>

394
00:22:24,192 --> 00:22:27,229
<font face="Serif" size="18">because those little plants</font>

395
00:22:27,229 --> 00:22:29,264
<font face="Serif" size="18">will shrivel up</font>

396
00:22:29,264 --> 00:22:33,135
<font face="Serif" size="18">and they will stop growing
in that environment.</font>

397
00:22:33,135 --> 00:22:37,305
<font face="Serif" size="18">Yes, be willing to impart
not just the many wonderful truths</font>

398
00:22:37,305 --> 00:22:39,941
<font face="Serif" size="18">of God’s Word that you learned at Gilead</font>

399
00:22:39,941 --> 00:22:43,879
<font face="Serif" size="18">but also your own heart and your own soul.</font>

400
00:22:43,879 --> 00:22:48,483
<font face="Serif" size="18">And then because those beautiful,
spiritual people you work with</font>

401
00:22:48,483 --> 00:22:51,720
<font face="Serif" size="18">will be properly instructed,</font>

402
00:22:51,720 --> 00:22:54,523
<font face="Serif" size="18">what will they be like?</font>

403
00:22:54,523 --> 00:22:58,493
<font face="Serif" size="18">They will be just like you.</font>

404
00:22:58,493 --> 00:23:01,563
<font face="Serif" size="18">And may the blessing
of our marvelous God, Jehovah,</font>

405
00:23:01,563 --> 00:23:03,832
<font face="Serif" size="18">go with you wherever you go.</font>

406
00:23:11,006 --> 00:23:13,241
<font face="Serif" size="18">Thank you very much, Brother Sanderson,</font>

407
00:23:13,241 --> 00:23:16,445
<font face="Serif" size="18">for that interesting Scriptural discussion</font>

408
00:23:16,445 --> 00:23:19,848
<font face="Serif" size="18">and some of those past experiences.</font>

409
00:23:19,848 --> 00:23:21,983
<font face="Serif" size="18">Of course, the brother might be saying,</font>

410
00:23:21,983 --> 00:23:24,586
<font face="Serif" size="18">‘You should have paid
closer attention to my talks.’</font>

411
00:23:25,053 --> 00:23:27,055
<font face="Serif" size="18">No, no.</font>

412
00:23:27,055 --> 00:23:29,224
<font face="Serif" size="18">It was obvious how much you loved him.</font>

413
00:23:30,392 --> 00:23:34,729
<font face="Serif" size="18">So, OK.</font>

414
00:23:34,729 --> 00:23:37,332
<font face="Serif" size="18">Clive Martin,
a helper to the Writing Committee,</font>

415
00:23:37,332 --> 00:23:41,169
<font face="Serif" size="18">is going to address us now
with this interesting theme,</font>

416
00:23:41,169 --> 00:23:44,439
<font face="Serif" size="18">“Remember the Terms of Peace?”</font>

417
00:23:46,475 --> 00:23:49,010
<font face="Serif" size="18">Have you ever had to sue for peace?</font>

418
00:23:50,312 --> 00:23:52,314
<font face="Serif" size="18">While you’re thinking of that question,</font>

419
00:23:52,314 --> 00:23:55,417
<font face="Serif" size="18">would you please turn with me
to Luke chapter 14?</font>

420
00:23:56,618 --> 00:23:58,920
<font face="Serif" size="18">I’d like to put you and me</font>

421
00:23:58,920 --> 00:24:01,790
<font face="Serif" size="18">in the middle of one of Jesus’ illustrations.</font>

422
00:24:01,790 --> 00:24:05,227
<font face="Serif" size="18">Jesus has been talking about what it costs</font>

423
00:24:05,227 --> 00:24:07,729
<font face="Serif" size="18">to become one of his disciples.</font>

424
00:24:07,729 --> 00:24:11,566
<font face="Serif" size="18">And then in verse 31, he says:</font>

425
00:24:11,566 --> 00:24:13,735
<font face="Serif" size="18">“Or what king</font>

426
00:24:13,735 --> 00:24:16,905
<font face="Serif" size="18">“[this is where we come in, what king]</font>

427
00:24:16,905 --> 00:24:19,207
<font face="Serif" size="18">“marching out against another king in war</font>

428
00:24:19,207 --> 00:24:23,945
<font face="Serif" size="18">“does not first sit down and take counsel
whether he is able with 10,000 troops</font>

429
00:24:23,945 --> 00:24:28,717
<font face="Serif" size="18">“to stand up to the one who comes
against him with 20,000?</font>

430
00:24:28,717 --> 00:24:30,819
<font face="Serif" size="18">“If, in fact, he cannot do so,</font>

431
00:24:30,819 --> 00:24:34,623
<font face="Serif" size="18">“then while that one is yet far away,</font>

432
00:24:34,623 --> 00:24:39,161
<font face="Serif" size="18">he sends out a body of ambassadors
and sues for peace.”</font>

433
00:24:41,062 --> 00:24:45,367
<font face="Serif" size="18">How do you think that conversation goes?</font>

434
00:24:45,367 --> 00:24:48,370
<font face="Serif" size="18">“I want peace, and these are my terms.”</font>

435
00:24:49,538 --> 00:24:50,705
<font face="Serif" size="18">Hardly!</font>

436
00:24:51,439 --> 00:24:55,110
<font face="Serif" size="18">It’s more like:
“I don’t want to be your enemy.</font>

437
00:24:55,110 --> 00:24:59,748
<font face="Serif" size="18">Please tell me what to do
so that I can have peace with you.”</font>

438
00:25:01,082 --> 00:25:05,987
<font face="Serif" size="18">Now, with that in mind,
Jesus gives the application, verse 33:</font>

439
00:25:05,987 --> 00:25:10,425
<font face="Serif" size="18">“In the same way, you may be sure
that not one of you</font>

440
00:25:10,425 --> 00:25:14,029
<font face="Serif" size="18">“who does not say good-bye
to all his belongings</font>

441
00:25:14,029 --> 00:25:16,031
<font face="Serif" size="18">can be my disciple.”</font>

442
00:25:17,432 --> 00:25:19,834
<font face="Serif" size="18">That is you and me.</font>

443
00:25:19,834 --> 00:25:21,836
<font face="Serif" size="18">We got to the point where we realized</font>

444
00:25:21,836 --> 00:25:24,606
<font face="Serif" size="18">we did not want to be an enemy of Jehovah.</font>

445
00:25:24,606 --> 00:25:28,510
<font face="Serif" size="18">And so we were willing
to sacrifice everything</font>

446
00:25:28,510 --> 00:25:32,147
<font face="Serif" size="18">—belongings, career, status, everything—</font>

447
00:25:32,147 --> 00:25:35,483
<font face="Serif" size="18">for the privilege of being
at peace with Jehovah</font>

448
00:25:35,483 --> 00:25:37,552
<font face="Serif" size="18">and being a disciple of his Son.</font>

449
00:25:38,286 --> 00:25:41,189
<font face="Serif" size="18">Now for you students of class 150,</font>

450
00:25:41,189 --> 00:25:43,792
<font face="Serif" size="18">your pursuit of peace with Jehovah</font>

451
00:25:43,792 --> 00:25:46,761
<font face="Serif" size="18">has led you
into the special full-time service.</font>

452
00:25:46,761 --> 00:25:50,765
<font face="Serif" size="18">And what a beautiful record
every one of you has set!</font>

453
00:25:52,100 --> 00:25:55,003
<font face="Serif" size="18">You remind me in many ways</font>

454
00:25:55,003 --> 00:25:57,339
<font face="Serif" size="18">of a group in the Bible</font>

455
00:25:57,339 --> 00:26:00,742
<font face="Serif" size="18">that literally sued for peace.</font>

456
00:26:00,742 --> 00:26:04,512
<font face="Serif" size="18">Their story is told
in the book of Joshua chapter 9.</font>

457
00:26:04,512 --> 00:26:08,717
<font face="Serif" size="18">That’s right;
we’re talking about the Gibeonites.</font>

458
00:26:08,717 --> 00:26:11,186
<font face="Serif" size="18">Do you have Joshua chapter 9?</font>

459
00:26:11,186 --> 00:26:14,990
<font face="Serif" size="18">Now, they had heard of all the things
that Jehovah had done</font>

460
00:26:14,990 --> 00:26:19,094
<font face="Serif" size="18">for his people, Israel, and to his enemies.</font>

461
00:26:19,094 --> 00:26:21,563
<font face="Serif" size="18">They did not want to be Jehovah’s enemy.</font>

462
00:26:21,563 --> 00:26:26,167
<font face="Serif" size="18">And so they did exactly
what the king in Jesus’ illustration did.</font>

463
00:26:26,167 --> 00:26:29,037
<font face="Serif" size="18">They sent a body of ambassadors.</font>

464
00:26:29,037 --> 00:26:31,973
<font face="Serif" size="18">So Joshua chapter 9</font>

465
00:26:31,973 --> 00:26:35,944
<font face="Serif" size="18">—and this is the opening overture</font>

466
00:26:35,944 --> 00:26:39,314
<font face="Serif" size="18">in verse 6:</font>

467
00:26:39,314 --> 00:26:41,816
<font face="Serif" size="18">“We have come from a distant land.</font>

468
00:26:41,816 --> 00:26:44,552
<font face="Serif" size="18">Now make a covenant with us.”</font>

469
00:26:45,787 --> 00:26:50,759
<font face="Serif" size="18">When they didn’t get a very warm
initial reception, they persisted.</font>

470
00:26:50,759 --> 00:26:54,663
<font face="Serif" size="18">Verse 8: “We are your servants.”</font>

471
00:26:54,663 --> 00:26:59,000
<font face="Serif" size="18">In other words,
“Set the terms; we want peace.”</font>

472
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:03,104
<font face="Serif" size="18">They were willing to sacrifice everything</font>

473
00:27:03,104 --> 00:27:07,108
<font face="Serif" size="18">in order to enjoy peace
with Israel and with Israel’s God.</font>

474
00:27:08,109 --> 00:27:11,646
<font face="Serif" size="18">Now, Joshua and the chieftains
didn’t see it exactly the same way,</font>

475
00:27:11,646 --> 00:27:14,449
<font face="Serif" size="18">particularly when they found out</font>

476
00:27:14,449 --> 00:27:17,352
<font face="Serif" size="18">that they were not from a distant land
as they had claimed.</font>

477
00:27:17,352 --> 00:27:19,354
<font face="Serif" size="18">Nobody likes to be fooled.</font>

478
00:27:19,354 --> 00:27:22,724
<font face="Serif" size="18">So the tone got a little sterner.</font>

479
00:27:22,724 --> 00:27:25,794
<font face="Serif" size="18">So turn and look at verse 23.</font>

480
00:27:25,794 --> 00:27:29,130
<font face="Serif" size="18">This is what they said:
“From now on you are cursed,</font>

481
00:27:29,130 --> 00:27:32,467
<font face="Serif" size="18">“and you will always occupy
a slave’s position</font>

482
00:27:32,467 --> 00:27:36,671
<font face="Serif" size="18">as gatherers of wood and drawers of water
for the house of my God.”</font>

483
00:27:38,306 --> 00:27:40,308
<font face="Serif" size="18">What will the Gibeonites say to that?</font>

484
00:27:41,443 --> 00:27:45,447
<font face="Serif" size="18">Verse 25: “We are at your mercy.</font>

485
00:27:45,447 --> 00:27:49,851
<font face="Serif" size="18">Do to us whatever you think
is good and right.”</font>

486
00:27:51,052 --> 00:27:54,723
<font face="Serif" size="18">And just so, the terms of peace were set.</font>

487
00:27:54,723 --> 00:27:58,660
<font face="Serif" size="18">Verse 27: “That day Joshua made them</font>

488
00:27:58,660 --> 00:28:01,129
<font face="Serif" size="18">“gatherers of wood and drawers of water</font>

489
00:28:01,129 --> 00:28:03,898
<font face="Serif" size="18">“for the assembly and for Jehovah’s altar</font>

490
00:28:03,898 --> 00:28:06,167
<font face="Serif" size="18">“at the place that He should choose,</font>

491
00:28:06,167 --> 00:28:08,436
<font face="Serif" size="18">and they remain so to this day.”</font>

492
00:28:09,904 --> 00:28:13,007
<font face="Serif" size="18">So now a few questions, a few lessons.</font>

493
00:28:13,007 --> 00:28:16,611
<font face="Serif" size="18">What do you think
of the Gibeonites’ assignment?</font>

494
00:28:17,479 --> 00:28:20,482
<font face="Serif" size="18">It was presented to them as a punishment.</font>

495
00:28:20,482 --> 00:28:22,250
<font face="Serif" size="18">But just think,</font>

496
00:28:22,250 --> 00:28:25,653
<font face="Serif" size="18">they weren’t being sold off
as household slaves.</font>

497
00:28:25,653 --> 00:28:29,224
<font face="Serif" size="18">Their humble service
would directly contribute</font>

498
00:28:29,224 --> 00:28:33,561
<font face="Serif" size="18">to pure worship and support Jehovah’s people.</font>

499
00:28:34,863 --> 00:28:36,865
<font face="Serif" size="18">That’s a privilege, isn’t it?</font>

500
00:28:36,865 --> 00:28:41,436
<font face="Serif" size="18">That’s the kind of service
we reach out for as a privilege.</font>

501
00:28:43,638 --> 00:28:46,007
<font face="Serif" size="18">Now, the kind of service—</font>

502
00:28:46,007 --> 00:28:49,444
<font face="Serif" size="18">Was it because they were lowly people,</font>

503
00:28:49,444 --> 00:28:54,349
<font face="Serif" size="18">no skills to do anything else,
that they were given this kind of job?</font>

504
00:28:54,349 --> 00:28:57,619
<font face="Serif" size="18">Well, look at chapter 10</font>

505
00:28:57,619 --> 00:28:59,621
<font face="Serif" size="18">and verse 2</font>

506
00:29:00,922 --> 00:29:03,191
<font face="Serif" size="18">and see the kind of people
the Gibeonites were:</font>

507
00:29:03,191 --> 00:29:07,429
<font face="Serif" size="18">“Gibeon was a great city,
like one of the royal cities.</font>

508
00:29:07,429 --> 00:29:11,866
<font face="Serif" size="18">“It was greater than Ai,
and all its men were warriors</font>

509
00:29:13,701 --> 00:29:16,771
<font face="Serif" size="18">[capable, skilled people].”</font>

510
00:29:16,771 --> 00:29:19,040
<font face="Serif" size="18">However,</font>

511
00:29:19,040 --> 00:29:21,142
<font face="Serif" size="18">clearly the Gibeonites realized</font>

512
00:29:21,142 --> 00:29:24,746
<font face="Serif" size="18">that if their army was no match for Israel,</font>

513
00:29:24,746 --> 00:29:27,449
<font face="Serif" size="18">then Jehovah didn’t need them</font>

514
00:29:27,449 --> 00:29:30,485
<font face="Serif" size="18">to bolster his army
in order to complete the conquest.</font>

515
00:29:30,485 --> 00:29:32,654
<font face="Serif" size="18">It was better for them</font>

516
00:29:32,654 --> 00:29:37,392
<font face="Serif" size="18">to ask Jehovah what he wanted them to do
and to do that.</font>

517
00:29:37,392 --> 00:29:42,363
<font face="Serif" size="18">So the sacrifice was definitely worth it.</font>

518
00:29:42,363 --> 00:29:47,135
<font face="Serif" size="18">Does that mean, though,
that their skills were irrelevant,</font>

519
00:29:47,135 --> 00:29:49,137
<font face="Serif" size="18">never even considered?</font>

520
00:29:49,838 --> 00:29:51,005
<font face="Serif" size="18">Well, no.</font>

521
00:29:51,005 --> 00:29:53,942
<font face="Serif" size="18">For example, a few hundred years later,</font>

522
00:29:53,942 --> 00:29:55,977
<font face="Serif" size="18">Ishmaiah the Gibeonite</font>

523
00:29:55,977 --> 00:29:59,881
<font face="Serif" size="18">is listed among David’s 30 mighty men.</font>

524
00:29:59,881 --> 00:30:03,918
<font face="Serif" size="18">Different needs call for different skills.</font>

525
00:30:03,918 --> 00:30:07,422
<font face="Serif" size="18">What did Ishmaiah do with his skill?</font>

526
00:30:07,422 --> 00:30:12,327
<font face="Serif" size="18">Well, he humbly defended pure worship
and Jehovah’s people.</font>

527
00:30:12,327 --> 00:30:15,563
<font face="Serif" size="18">So the details of the assignment
were different,</font>

528
00:30:15,563 --> 00:30:18,299
<font face="Serif" size="18">but the focus was about the same.</font>

529
00:30:20,735 --> 00:30:23,671
<font face="Serif" size="18">Another question: Was this just</font>

530
00:30:23,671 --> 00:30:26,574
<font face="Serif" size="18">a short-term starter assignment?</font>

531
